<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-248-134  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 248 134.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 1 1989 v8 n9 p82(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Rep. Wise urges Govt., users to cooperate in revising laws.andO;(Robert E. Wise Jr.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Price, Douglas S.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Freedom of Information Act (analysis).andO;Topic:     United States. Congress. House. Subcommittee on GovernmentInformation, Justice, and AgricultureNational GovernmentInformation Resources ManagementLegal IssuesGovernment Agency.andO;Person:    Wise, Robert E., Jr. (addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Rep.andP;  Wise Urges Govt., Users To Cooperate in Revising LawsandM;Most federal laws concerning information abuse were written when hard copywas the only format.andP;  Now the federal government's information disseminationprocess is badly out of date, according to Rep.andP;  Robert E. Wise Jr., chairmanof the House Government Operations Subcommittee on Government Information,Justice and Agriculture.andM;In his keynote address at the Federal Library and Information CenterCommittee's sixth annual forum on federal information policies in Washington,the West Virginia Democrat said changes in the laws are needed, but whatthese changes should be is not clear.andP;  To cope with the problem, he urged acooperative approach between the Congress and the executive branch, with muchinvolvement of the user community.andM;All three branches of the federal government, as well as the public, haveroles in establishing information policies, he said.andP;  For example, he said,the substantial body of First Amendment law is almost all derived fromjudicial opinions.andM;As a more complex example of the interrelationships among the three branchesand the public, Wise described the evolution of the Freedom of InformationAct (FOIA).andP;  The original FOIA was well-intentioned, he said, but theexemptions were too broad and allowed agencies to withhold information thatdid not really require confidentiality.andP;  He said agencies insisted onfollowing the letter of the law, rather than its spirit, to avoid almost alldisclosure.andM;Recognizing that FOIA was not accomplishing its intended purpose, Congress in1974 enacted over a presidential veto major amendments to narrow theloopholes, he said.andP;  For the first time, he said, FOIA became an effectivetool for obtaining disclosure of information.andM;Requests to the agencies citing FOIA became far more frequent, to the pointof overwhelming some agencies' ability to respond.andP;  However, Wise observed,delays now are attributable to the volume of requests, not bureaucraticinaction.andO;</TEXT></DOC>